Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.35,0:00:02.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine for a moment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.69,0:00:05.06,Default,,0,0,0,,that you’re going on a trip. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.06,0:00:07.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The tickets are a gift; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.29,0:00:09.56,Default,,0,0,0,,a friend has paid the price. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.56,0:00:12.30,Default,,0,0,0,,All you have to do is pack your bags \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.30,0:00:14.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and get to the airport. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.30,0:00:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Now as you know, packing isn’t easy, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.87,0:00:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and dragging heavy bags \Naround the airport is exhausting. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.01,0:00:24.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember the days \Nbefore luggage had wheels? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.61,0:00:26.61,Default,,0,0,0,,How did we do that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.61,0:00:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Heavy baggage can make even a vacation \Nseem like a burden. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.35,0:00:34.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the point is this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.42,0:00:37.89,Default,,0,0,0,,You and I have set out on an exciting journey \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.89,0:00:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—a journey to God’s new world. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.36,0:00:44.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The trip is free; the ransom paid the price. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.29,0:00:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,All we have to do is get there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.76,0:00:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s the hard part, right? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.03,0:00:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,And why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.04,0:00:54.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Because each one of us is carrying \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.60,0:00:58.61,Default,,0,0,0,,some type of heavy baggage on this journey. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.61,0:01:01.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, it’s true our life is blessed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.01,0:01:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,As Isaiah 65:13 says, figuratively, \Nwe’re eating and drinking \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.85,0:01:08.99,Default,,0,0,0,,while the world goes hungry and thirsty. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.99,0:01:12.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, Acts 14:22 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.09,0:01:14.29,Default,,0,0,0,,“We must enter into the Kingdom of God \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.29,0:01:16.53,Default,,0,0,0,,through many tribulations.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.53,0:01:19.33,Default,,0,0,0,,We have anxieties. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.33,0:01:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And Proverbs 12:25 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.73,0:01:25.10,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Anxiety in the heart can weigh it down.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.10,0:01:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The heavy baggage we carry \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.84,0:01:31.01,Default,,0,0,0,,can make even the journey to God’s new world \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.01,0:01:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,seem like a burden. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.58,0:01:36.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the good news is that we have help. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.15,0:01:42.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Open your Bible to 1 Kings 8:38, 39. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.35,0:01:45.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Here Solomon prayed \Non behalf of Jehovah’s people \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.86,0:01:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,at the inauguration of the temple. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.69,0:01:50.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And what he said in that prayer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.79,0:01:52.86,Default,,0,0,0,,can help us put wheels on our baggage \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.86,0:01:54.93,Default,,0,0,0,,so it’s easier for us to carry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.93,0:01:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,At 1 Kings 8, beginning with verse 38, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.77,0:02:00.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Solomon says to Jehovah: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.84,0:02:04.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“Whatever prayer, whatever request for favor \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.61,0:02:08.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“may be made by any man \Nor by all your people Israel \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.81,0:02:13.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“(for each one knows the plague \Nof his own heart) \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.02,0:02:15.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“when they spread out their hands \Ntoward this house, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.99,0:02:19.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“then may you hear from the heavens, \Nyour dwelling place, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.36,0:02:22.36,Default,,0,0,0,,and may you forgive and take action.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.36,0:02:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s stop there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.36,0:02:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice that phrase \N“each one knows the plague of his own heart.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.20,0:02:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,In stating that, Solomon wasn’t referring \Nto the nation as a whole. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.14,0:02:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,He was referring to private suffering \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.51,0:02:41.25,Default,,0,0,0,,—the baggage each person had to carry, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.24,0:02:44.91,Default,,0,0,0,,the problems no one else might know about. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.91,0:02:49.15,Default,,0,0,0,,And although Solomon evidently had \Na specific type of plague in mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.15,0:02:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,—one that required forgiveness—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.29,0:02:56.30,Default,,0,0,0,,by extension his words can apply \Nto any anxiety that weighs us down. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.29,0:03:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nchapter 2 of the “God’s Love” book \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.40,0:03:03.70,Default,,0,0,0,,applies Solomon’s words \Nto a personal weakness \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.70,0:03:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,we might struggle with. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.87,0:03:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,The May 1, 2010, Watchtower applies it \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.11,0:03:12.95,Default,,0,0,0,,to the grief a person feels \Nafter losing a mate. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.94,0:03:15.24,Default,,0,0,0,,The point is: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.25,0:03:18.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Any anxiety that weighs us down \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.62,0:03:21.01,Default,,0,0,0,,can be considered a plague of the heart. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.42,0:03:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What is the plague of your heart? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.12,0:03:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What anxiety weighs you down \Non your journey to God’s new world? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.53,0:03:36.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever baggage we carry, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.20,0:03:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,the scripture we just read \Nconfirms that we have help. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.74,0:03:41.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice, Solomon prayed that Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.80,0:03:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,would not only “hear from the heavens” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.24,0:03:46.71,Default,,0,0,0,,but also “take action” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.71,0:03:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—if not to eliminate our load \Nthen at least to help us carry it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.12,0:03:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,For the rest of this discussion, \Nwe’ll see how Jehovah can do that \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.45,0:03:57.45,Default,,0,0,0,,in three situations: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.45,0:04:01.12,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) when circumstances discourage us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.12,0:04:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,(2) when people upset us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.03,0:04:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and (3) when negative emotions \Noverwhelm us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.60,0:04:11.84,Default,,0,0,0,,In all situations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.83,0:04:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah can help us cope \Nwith the plague of our heart. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.61,0:04:17.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s see how. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.17,0:04:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,First, when circumstances discourage us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.45,0:04:24.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, when it comes to circumstances, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.68,0:04:26.75,Default,,0,0,0,,life is unpredictable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.75,0:04:29.89,Default,,0,0,0,,In this system, \Nthings can change just like that \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.89,0:04:32.09,Default,,0,0,0,,with one phone call, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.09,0:04:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,one accident, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.26,0:04:36.36,Default,,0,0,0,,one diagnosis. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.36,0:04:38.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me tell you about Anny, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.36,0:04:42.13,Default,,0,0,0,,who was diagnosed at age 19 \Nwith pulmonary fibrosis, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.13,0:04:46.53,Default,,0,0,0,,and at first she felt \Nthis was completely unfair. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.54,0:04:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Anny says: “Pulmonary fibrosis \Naffects heavy smokers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.54,0:04:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“and I had never had a cigarette in my life! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.01,0:04:57.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“I was depressed, I wouldn’t eat, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.35,0:04:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“and I wouldn’t talk to people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.52,0:05:01.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“I would just lie in bed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.55,0:05:04.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and think about how miserable my life was.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.69,0:05:08.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Anny is one of Jehovah’s Witnesses, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.12,0:05:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and she was one when she got sick. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.96,0:05:15.03,Default,,0,0,0,,She understood the real cause of her illness, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.03,0:05:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and she knew about the new world. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.13,0:05:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, this discouraging circumstance \Nthrew Anny off course. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.41,0:05:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,She says, “I prayed and prayed \Nand prayed about it, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.88,0:05:28.01,Default,,0,0,0,,but it felt like I was just talking \Nto the wall.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.05,0:05:32.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, regardless of our age, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.82,0:05:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,we may relate to Anny’s comment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.82,0:05:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,When any of us face \Na discouraging circumstance, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.22,0:05:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,we pray about it repeatedly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.29,0:05:43.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And if nothing changes, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.29,0:05:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,we may wonder whether Jehovah cares about \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.20,0:05:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,or even sees what we’re going through. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.93,0:05:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,A discouraging circumstance \Ncan become a plague of our heart. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.94,0:05:56.94,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we cope with it? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.94,0:06:01.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let’s look at 2 Corinthians 12:7-9. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.71,0:06:06.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Here the apostle Paul \Nfaced a discouraging circumstance \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.15,0:06:08.65,Default,,0,0,0,,—one that he calls “a thorn in the flesh.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.65,0:06:11.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as you realize, \Nwe don’t know what that thorn was. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.32,0:06:13.62,Default,,0,0,0,,It might have been a physical affliction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.62,0:06:16.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever it was, as we read these verses, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.06,0:06:18.06,Default,,0,0,0,,try to detect two things: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.06,0:06:21.06,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) what Paul could not control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.06,0:06:23.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and (2) what he could control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.97,0:06:27.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Second Corinthians 12, \Nbeginning with verse 7: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.77,0:06:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“To keep me from becoming overly exalted, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.21,0:06:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“I was given a thorn in the flesh, \Nan angel of Satan, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.41,0:06:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“to keep slapping me, \Nso that I might not be overly exalted. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.42,0:06:44.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“Three times I begged the Lord about this, \Nthat it would depart from me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.72,0:06:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“But he said to me: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.72,0:06:49.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘My undeserved kindness \Nis sufficient for you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.89,0:06:53.73,Default,,0,0,0,,for my power is being \Nmade perfect in weakness.’” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.73,0:06:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s stop there \Nand look at our two components. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.10,0:07:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,First, what couldn’t Paul control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.70,0:07:02.70,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer is obvious \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.71,0:07:05.98,Default,,0,0,0,,—the circumstance itself—\Nhis “thorn in the flesh.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.98,0:07:08.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul even prayed about it three times, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.78,0:07:10.95,Default,,0,0,0,,but nothing changed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.95,0:07:15.29,Default,,0,0,0,,The circumstance was beyond his control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.28,0:07:17.55,Default,,0,0,0,,What could Paul control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.55,0:07:19.55,Default,,0,0,0,,His response. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.56,0:07:23.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And part of that response \Nwas to accept the reality \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.43,0:07:26.53,Default,,0,0,0,,of his situation \Nto the point that he says in verse 9: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.53,0:07:30.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“Most gladly, . . . \NI will boast about my weaknesses.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.47,0:07:35.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Once Paul realized \Nthat his thorn would not be removed, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.17,0:07:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,he didn’t waste time doubting God’s love \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.34,0:07:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,or asking ‘Why me?’ \Nor comparing himself to others \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.28,0:07:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,who seemed to have an easier life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.45,0:07:47.95,Default,,0,0,0,,No, Paul accepted reality. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.95,0:07:50.79,Default,,0,0,0,,He viewed his thorn as “an angel of Satan,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.79,0:07:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,and he got about the business of endurance. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.22,0:07:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Paul’s experience gives us a key \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.83,0:07:59.57,Default,,0,0,0,,to coping with any discouraging circumstance. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.56,0:08:02.30,Default,,0,0,0,,First, break it down into two components: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.30,0:08:05.07,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) what we can’t control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.07,0:08:08.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and (2) what we can. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.07,0:08:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,And often, like Paul, \Nwhat we can control is our response. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.88,0:08:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,That is a choice. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.65,0:08:18.52,Default,,0,0,0,,When we face a discouraging circumstance, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.51,0:08:23.18,Default,,0,0,0,,we could choose to become bitter about life, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.19,0:08:25.66,Default,,0,0,0,,angry at God. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.66,0:08:29.50,Default,,0,0,0,,We could even let it stumble us as some have. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.49,0:08:32.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Or we can choose a better response. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.46,0:08:36.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And like Paul, \Na better response usually involves \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.40,0:08:40.97,Default,,0,0,0,,first accepting the reality of the situation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.97,0:08:45.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, at first that might sound cold, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.24,0:08:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,but accepting reality is vital. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.84,0:08:49.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.85,0:08:54.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Page 7 of the April 2014 Awake! says this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.55,0:08:57.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“By learning to accept \Nwhat you cannot change, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.99,0:09:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“. . . you are also more likely to look \Nfor ways to cope with the situation . . . \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.06,0:09:05.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“You start to take a measure of control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.16,0:09:09.70,Default,,0,0,0,,of what seems to be \Nan uncontrollable situation.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.70,0:09:12.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Harold King is an example of that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.87,0:09:16.01,Default,,0,0,0,,As you know, he was imprisoned for his faith, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.01,0:09:19.28,Default,,0,0,0,,confined to a four-and-a-half \Nby nine-foot cell. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.28,0:09:23.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother King certainly couldn’t control \Nhis circumstance, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.25,0:09:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,but he could control his response. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.42,0:09:30.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Once Brother King \Naccepted the reality of his situation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.29,0:09:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,he thought of things that he could control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.72,0:09:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,—things that even prison walls \Ncould not prevent him from doing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.29,0:09:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,For example: He prayed; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.63,0:09:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,he memorized scriptures; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.80,0:09:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,he wrote Kingdom songs; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.00,0:09:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,he celebrated the Memorial \Nright there in his cell alone; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.97,0:09:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,he even went out in service \Nby creating imaginary householders. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.98,0:09:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Once Brother King accepted reality, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.98,0:09:59.05,Default,,0,0,0,,he was able to take a measure of control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.05,0:10:03.89,Default,,0,0,0,,of what seemed to be \Nan uncontrollable situation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.89,0:10:06.89,Default,,0,0,0,,A brother whose wife \Nwas diagnosed with cancer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.89,0:10:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,relates how they did something similar. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.59,0:10:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,They couldn’t control the disease. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.43,0:10:15.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But what could they do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.23,0:10:19.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Quoted in the August 2011 Awake! \Nthe husband says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.97,0:10:22.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“We decided that at regular intervals \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.37,0:10:26.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“we would not talk \Nabout the cancer for a whole day. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.18,0:10:29.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“Instead, we focused \Non the positive aspects of our life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.85,0:10:33.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“It was like taking a vacation \Nfrom the disease. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.62,0:10:37.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Regularly we had a cancer-free day.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.32,0:10:40.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that’s how this couple \Ntook a measure of control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.76,0:10:43.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Others might choose a different method, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.13,0:10:45.53,Default,,0,0,0,,but again the point is this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.53,0:10:48.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Once we accept reality, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.46,0:10:52.30,Default,,0,0,0,,we’re more likely to find ways \Nto cope with the situation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.30,0:10:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and to even take a measure \Nof control over it.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.77,0:11:00.77,Default,,0,0,0,,But is accepting reality all we can do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.78,0:11:03.25,Default,,0,0,0,,No, there’s something more. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.25,0:11:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The article \N“Learning to Live with the Unchangeable” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.48,0:11:11.32,Default,,0,0,0,,in the March 15, 1978, Watchtower \Nsuggests this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.32,0:11:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“In whatever state or condition \Nyou might find yourself, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.86,0:11:20.87,Default,,0,0,0,,look for its compensations or mercies.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.86,0:11:25.03,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s exactly what Paul did \Nin connection with his thorn. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.03,0:11:28.23,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, look back at 2 Corinthians 12. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.24,0:11:32.51,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 7, twice Paul says \Nthat his thorn kept him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.51,0:11:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,“from becoming overly exalted.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.81,0:11:37.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Humility—that’s one compensation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.75,0:11:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 9, Paul says God’s power \Nis “made perfect in weakness.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.75,0:11:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Increased reliance on Jehovah \N—that’s a second compensation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.76,0:11:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s a third. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.76,0:11:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at Philippians 4:11. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.73,0:11:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Philippians was written \Nabout five or six years \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.37,0:12:01.01,Default,,0,0,0,,after Paul wrote to the Corinthians \Nabout his thorn in the flesh. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.00,0:12:05.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So that thorn may have been \None of the things on Paul’s mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.44,0:12:08.61,Default,,0,0,0,,as he wrote what we’re about to read. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.61,0:12:13.62,Default,,0,0,0,,At Philippians 4:11, \Nthe second part of the verse, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.62,0:12:17.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul says: \N“I have learned to be self-sufficient \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.69,0:12:21.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“[or according to the footnote, “content”] \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.12,0:12:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,regardless of my circumstances.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.39,0:12:26.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, with these words, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.83,0:12:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul expresses a vital truth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.20,0:12:33.54,Default,,0,0,0,,that contentment, even happiness, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.54,0:12:37.95,Default,,0,0,0,,does not depend \Non having ideal circumstances. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.94,0:12:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, sometimes we talk as if it does. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.51,0:12:42.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We say things like: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.51,0:12:45.15,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’ll be happy \Nwhen I get a better work assignment’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.15,0:12:47.85,Default,,0,0,0,,or ‘I’ll be happy when I get married.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.85,0:12:50.79,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’ll be happy when I get a better room.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.79,0:12:53.56,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’ll be happy when I get a better roommate.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.56,0:12:58.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The idea is: ‘I’ll only be happy \Nwhen my circumstances change.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.20,0:13:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s been said that people who think that way \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.76,0:13:04.73,Default,,0,0,0,,strive and strive but never arrive \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.73,0:13:06.73,Default,,0,0,0,,because as soon as they get that circumstance \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.74,0:13:08.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that was supposed to make them happy, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.74,0:13:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,another obstacle looms up \Nand they’re discontent again. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.68,0:13:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul chose to be content, \Ndespite his circumstances. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.45,0:13:22.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And notice, he says in verse 11: \N“I have learned” this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.18,0:13:26.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Contentment might not have been \Nhis default position. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.29,0:13:28.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps like many of us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.29,0:13:32.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul had a tendency \Nto veer towards negativity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.29,0:13:35.13,Default,,0,0,0,,when confronted with a trial. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.13,0:13:38.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But Paul learned to be content \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.30,0:13:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,even when his repeated prayers for relief \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.60,0:13:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,were not answered \Nthe way he would have liked. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.24,0:13:47.64,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, we could summarize \Nthe lesson Paul learned this way: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.64,0:13:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t let the blessing you’re praying for \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.88,0:13:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,blind you to the compensations \Nand mercies you have. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.15,0:13:58.82,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, sometimes \Nwhen we’re going through a trial, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.82,0:14:02.26,Default,,0,0,0,,we tend to narrow the focus \Nof our prayers by, in effect, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.26,0:14:05.40,Default,,0,0,0,,telling Jehovah how we expect to be blessed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.39,0:14:10.03,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, Jehovah may already be giving us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.03,0:14:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,compensations and mercies \Nthat we haven’t considered. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.00,0:14:18.37,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s what Anny, the sister \Nwith pulmonary fibrosis, came to learn. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.37,0:14:20.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember how she said, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.38,0:14:22.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“I prayed and prayed and prayed, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.51,0:14:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,but it felt like I was just talking \Nto the wall”? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.32,0:14:30.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Anny also admits, \N“At first, I was even mad at Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.92,0:14:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,for not helping me \Nin the way I wanted to be helped.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.72,0:14:38.82,Default,,0,0,0,,How did Anny come to see \Ncompensations and mercies \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.83,0:14:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,even in the midst of a serious illness? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.90,0:14:43.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s what she says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.17,0:14:46.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“My dad opened my eyes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.37,0:14:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“While I was so upset at Jehovah, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.57,0:14:52.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“my dad wouldn’t stop \Npraying to him and thanking him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.14,0:14:55.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“and talking about \Nhow good Jehovah had been to me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.64,0:14:58.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“I had just been through \Nthe worst months of my life, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.88,0:15:00.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“and my dad was thanking Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.88,0:15:02.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘For what?’ I asked him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.89,0:15:04.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“He told me: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.89,0:15:08.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘You have no idea \Nhow expensive your medicine was, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.19,0:15:10.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and I wasn’t even working. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.86,0:15:13.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Somehow we managed \Nto get everything we needed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.83,0:15:15.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘There was always food in the house. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.83,0:15:18.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Brothers kept coming \Nto make sure we were eating. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.73,0:15:23.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah gave us the strength \Nto keep going and not give up.’” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.37,0:15:26.44,Default,,0,0,0,,And then Anny’s dad told her this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.44,0:15:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“Just because Jehovah didn’t help you \Nthe way you wanted to be helped \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.21,0:15:33.61,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn’t mean he didn’t do it.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.62,0:15:36.06,Default,,0,0,0,,In essence, her dad was saying, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.05,0:15:38.89,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Don’t let the blessing you’re praying for \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.89,0:15:43.36,Default,,0,0,0,,blind you to the compensations \Nand mercies you have.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.36,0:15:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Anny now says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.43,0:15:48.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah helps us \Nin ways we can’t see at first \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.43,0:15:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“because we’re so overwhelmed \Nby what we’re going through. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.03,0:15:55.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“But I’ve learned that Jehovah \Nhas a way of doing things, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.77,0:16:00.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and his way is always better than my way.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.78,0:16:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,We can adopt a similar viewpoint. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.85,0:16:08.22,Default,,0,0,0,,If we can see the compensations \Nand mercies in our situation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.22,0:16:11.56,Default,,0,0,0,,then we’ll be better able \Nto cope with a circumstance \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.55,0:16:15.22,Default,,0,0,0,,that has become a plague of our heart.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.22,0:16:17.22,Default,,0,0,0,,So to review: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.23,0:16:20.33,Default,,0,0,0,,How can the apostle Paul’s example \Nlighten our load \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.33,0:16:23.50,Default,,0,0,0,,when a discouraging circumstance \Nis weighing us down? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.50,0:16:26.84,Default,,0,0,0,,First, accept the reality of the situation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.84,0:16:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,That may open our minds \Nto practical ways to deal with it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.84,0:16:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, look for compensations and mercies. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.88,0:16:37.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t let the blessing you’re praying for \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.18,0:16:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,blind you to the blessings you have. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.98,0:16:42.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Those two suggestions can help us cope \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.99,0:16:45.23,Default,,0,0,0,,with a discouraging circumstance \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.22,0:16:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that has become a plague of our heart. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.33,0:16:53.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s move on to our second point: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.16,0:16:57.97,Default,,0,0,0,,when people upset us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.97,0:17:02.98,Default,,0,0,0,,A sister we’ll call Helen \Nhas been pioneering for six years. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.97,0:17:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,She serves as a construction volunteer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.41,0:17:10.45,Default,,0,0,0,,She helped out for an extended period \Non the Warwick project. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.45,0:17:15.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Needless to say, \NHelen has been around a lot of people \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.22,0:17:18.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—Jehovah’s people—\Nand that’s a blessing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.35,0:17:21.99,Default,,0,0,0,,But Helen admits that at times \Nit’s also been a test. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.99,0:17:23.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.99,0:17:26.79,Default,,0,0,0,,She says: \N“One of my greatest weaknesses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.80,0:17:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“is a critical eye toward others. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.67,0:17:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“Rarely do I have \Na good first impression of a person; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.44,0:17:36.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“it’s always tainted \Nby some negative observation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.64,0:17:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“At first, even the best of people \Nseem too quick to laugh, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.51,0:17:43.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“too popular, even too spiritual. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.48,0:17:47.08,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s a terrible, ugly weakness I have.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.08,0:17:50.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, perhaps we can relate \Nto Helen’s comment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.72,0:17:54.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We might tend to get annoyed \Nor even hold a grudge \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.59,0:17:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,when someone says or does the wrong thing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.86,0:18:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And we think that tendency will change \Nwhen we come to Bethel, right? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.20,0:18:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Finally, I’ll be around people \Nwho are easy to get along with.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.67,0:18:07.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And then at some point \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.07,0:18:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,—whether it’s after a few months \Nor a few minutes—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.77,0:18:12.94,Default,,0,0,0,,the bubble bursts, \Nand now we’re not sure \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.94,0:18:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,whether the brotherhood is a blessing \Nfrom Jehovah or a test from Satan. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.51,0:18:22.95,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we cope with that \Nwhen people upset us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.95,0:18:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let’s look at Romans 12:18. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.72,0:18:30.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And as we read Romans 12:18, \Ntry to detect two things: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.23,0:18:33.77,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) what we can’t control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.76,0:18:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and (2) what we can control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.90,0:18:39.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Romans 12:18 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.77,0:18:44.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“If possible, as far as it depends on you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.77,0:18:47.21,Default,,0,0,0,,be peaceable with all men.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.21,0:18:49.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s look at our two components. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.65,0:18:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,First, what can’t we control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.58,0:18:55.15,Default,,0,0,0,,What others say or do; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.15,0:18:58.15,Default,,0,0,0,,that part depends on them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.15,0:19:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,What can we control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.66,0:19:04.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, it’s our response \N—that is a choice. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.96,0:19:08.73,Default,,0,0,0,,When someone upsets us, \Nwe can choose to let it grow \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.73,0:19:10.80,Default,,0,0,0,,or we can choose to let it go. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.80,0:19:13.64,Default,,0,0,0,,We can choose to “be peaceable with all men.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.64,0:19:17.18,Default,,0,0,0,,That part, Romans 12:18 says, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.17,0:19:20.31,Default,,0,0,0,,depends on each one of us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.31,0:19:23.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So how can we choose to be peaceable \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.95,0:19:25.95,Default,,0,0,0,,when someone upsets us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.95,0:19:27.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let’s look at Judges 8:2. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.95,0:19:31.32,Default,,0,0,0,,This shows us one thing we can do, \NJudges 8:2. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.32,0:19:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Here Gideon avoided \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.39,0:19:36.73,Default,,0,0,0,,what could have turned out \Nto be a messy conflict. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.73,0:19:38.73,Default,,0,0,0,,You remember the story. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.73,0:19:42.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Gideon and his army \Nhad just won a battle against Midian. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:42.87,0:19:47.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And at that point, \Nthe tribe of Ephraim starts complaining. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.77,0:19:50.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, even though they \Nwere eventually called into the battle \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.81,0:19:54.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and even though they captured \Ntwo Midianite princes, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.51,0:19:58.75,Default,,0,0,0,,the Ephraimites felt that they \Nshould have been called in sooner \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.75,0:20:00.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and they blamed this all on Gideon. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.75,0:20:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Judges 8:1 says that “they quarreled \Nbitterly with him” about this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.59,0:20:06.96,Default,,0,0,0,,So now there’s a conflict. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.96,0:20:08.96,Default,,0,0,0,,How did Gideon handle it? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.96,0:20:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what he says \Nto the tribe of Ephraim at Judges 8:2: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.26,0:20:17.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“What have I done compared with you? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.37,0:20:22.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Are not the gleanings of Ephraim \Nbetter than the grape harvest of Abiezer?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.37,0:20:25.71,Default,,0,0,0,,What does that last question mean? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.71,0:20:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, Gideon was from the family of Abiezer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.14,0:20:33.41,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what he’s saying to the Ephraimites is: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.42,0:20:36.76,Default,,0,0,0,,‘The grapes that your tribe leaves behind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.75,0:20:40.65,Default,,0,0,0,,are better than the best grapes \Nmy family can grow.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.66,0:20:42.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And then he reminds the Ephraimites \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.72,0:20:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,that they had an important role \Nin the battle, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.76,0:20:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and again he asks them: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.76,0:20:48.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“What have I done compared with you?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.96,0:20:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Verse 3 says that after that \Nthe Ephraimites “calmed down.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:54.54,0:20:57.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Problem solved—and how? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.37,0:20:59.37,Default,,0,0,0,,What did Gideon do here? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.37,0:21:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,In the face of a conflict \Nwith the Ephraimites, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.78,0:21:03.78,Default,,0,0,0,,he did not put them down. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.78,0:21:05.32,Default,,0,0,0,,He raised them up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.31,0:21:07.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He found something good about them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.32,0:21:12.86,Default,,0,0,0,,—in this case, their grape harvest, \Nsomething totally unrelated to the conflict—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.85,0:21:17.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and for the sake of peace, \Nhe praised them for it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.93,0:21:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we can take a similar approach. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.03,0:21:25.77,Default,,0,0,0,,When someone upsets us, \Nlook for the “grape harvest.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.77,0:21:27.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if it’s just to ourselves, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.77,0:21:30.44,Default,,0,0,0,,we can find something good \Nabout the person, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.44,0:21:34.75,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps something totally unrelated \Nto the conflict we’re having. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.74,0:21:39.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that’s what Helen, \Nthe sister I quoted earlier, is trying to do. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.75,0:21:44.19,Default,,0,0,0,,She says: “For every bad thought \NI have toward a person, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.19,0:21:47.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“I try to make myself \Nfind something good about them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.62,0:21:50.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“When I take that step back, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.36,0:21:55.37,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s easier for me to get to know a person \Nfrom a loving standpoint.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.36,0:21:57.80,Default,,0,0,0,,We can do the same thing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.80,0:22:00.34,Default,,0,0,0,,When someone upsets us, \Ntake that step back; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.34,0:22:02.34,Default,,0,0,0,,look for the “grape harvest.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.34,0:22:04.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Find the good in that person. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.37,0:22:06.61,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s the first thing we can do. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.61,0:22:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, a second thing we can do \Nis identified in Galatians chapter 2. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.35,0:22:12.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.15,0:22:14.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And before we read from this chapter, \NGalatians 2, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.98,0:22:17.32,Default,,0,0,0,,consider this question: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.32,0:22:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Who are we most likely to get upset at? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.82,0:22:25.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably someone who wrongs us, \Nwouldn’t you think? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.13,0:22:27.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But you know, there’s one type of person \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.23,0:22:29.93,Default,,0,0,0,,we might be even more prone to get upset at. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.93,0:22:31.63,Default,,0,0,0,,You know who it is? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:31.63,0:22:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Not someone who wrongs us,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.87,0:22:38.44,Default,,0,0,0,,but someone who “rights” us \Nby giving us correction when we need it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.44,0:22:41.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And in Galatians 2, \Nwe’re going to see an example of that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.51,0:22:45.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Here Peter was given correction, \Nand he needed it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.51,0:22:48.48,Default,,0,0,0,,But notice how the correction was given, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.48,0:22:50.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and then we’ll see why, in this case, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.82,0:22:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,it might have been exceptionally hard \Nfor Peter to accept it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.89,0:22:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,At Galatians 2:11, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.43,0:23:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul writes: “However, when Cephas \N[that’s Peter] came to Antioch, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.53,0:23:06.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“I resisted him face-to-face, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.54,0:23:09.51,Default,,0,0,0,,because he was clearly in the wrong.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.50,0:23:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul is upset at Peter, and why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.21,0:23:14.21,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 12, he tells us: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.21,0:23:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“For before certain men from James arrived \N[those who were Jewish Christians], \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.31,0:23:21.41,Default,,0,0,0,,“[Peter] used to eat \Nwith people of the nations; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.42,0:23:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“but when they arrived, he stopped doing this \Nand separated himself, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.19,0:23:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,fearing those of the circumcised class.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.26,0:23:30.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what’s Paul saying here? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.63,0:23:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That Peter would change how he acted \Ndepending on who was watching, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.00,0:23:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and Paul called him out on this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.00,0:23:39.64,Default,,0,0,0,,He says: “I resisted [Peter] face-to-face.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.63,0:23:42.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And then in verse 14, \NPaul really gives it to Peter. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.40,0:23:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,He tells him straight out: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.11,0:23:46.78,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You act one way \Nwhen the Jewish Christians are watching \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.78,0:23:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and another way \Nwhen their backs are turned.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.01,0:23:52.65,Default,,0,0,0,,In verse 13, Paul calls this a “pretense,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.65,0:23:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,or as the footnote renders it “hypocrisy.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.22,0:24:03.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine: Paul is calling Peter a hypocrite. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.13,0:24:07.93,Default,,0,0,0,,And he does this not privately \Nbut “before them all,” verse 14 says. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.93,0:24:09.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Can this get any worse? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.93,0:24:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, and it did. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.77,0:24:16.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Under inspiration, \NPaul wrote about this incident \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.97,0:24:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,in his letter to the Galatians, \Nwhich we just read from. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.74,0:24:23.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, to make a comparison: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.21,0:24:28.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, Internet messages spread \Nfrom one person to the next. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.15,0:24:33.05,Default,,0,0,0,,And when a message \Ncirculates rapidly and widely, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.05,0:24:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,people say it went viral. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.82,0:24:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, they didn’t have the Internet \Nin the first century, of course, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.93,0:24:43.34,Default,,0,0,0,,but they did have letters \N—and letters circulated. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.33,0:24:45.83,Default,,0,0,0,,And this one, Galatians, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.83,0:24:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,did more than just circulate \Nfrom one person to the next \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.60,0:24:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,or even one congregation to the next. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.87,0:24:54.67,Default,,0,0,0,,No, under Jehovah’s supervision, \Nthis one ended up in the Bible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.68,0:24:58.59,Default,,0,0,0,,—billions of copies down \Nthrough the centuries still being printed, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.58,0:25:00.92,Default,,0,0,0,,translated into thousands of languages. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.92,0:25:04.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now the whole world can read \Nabout Peter’s hypocrisy, as we just did. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.96,0:25:11.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the Bible doesn’t tell us \NPeter’s immediate reaction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.23,0:25:15.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Initially, he may have been upset \Nat Paul, for all we know. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.03,0:25:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,But in the end, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.03,0:25:19.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter chose to be peaceable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.03,0:25:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,How do we know that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.04,0:25:25.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in his second letter, \Nwhich was written about 12 to 14 years later, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.51,0:25:29.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter called Paul “our beloved brother,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.28,0:25:32.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and he even said \Nthat Paul had God-given wisdom. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.41,0:25:35.58,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s at 2 Peter 3:15. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.58,0:25:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So in the end, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.69,0:25:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter looked up to Paul, \Nand for good reason. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.09,0:25:44.59,Default,,0,0,0,,As he acknowledged, \NPaul had God-given wisdom \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.59,0:25:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,to see not only into Scripture \Nbut also into people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.60,0:25:51.60,Default,,0,0,0,,He could even see into Peter. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.60,0:25:54.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And instead of viewing that as a threat, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.70,0:25:57.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter saw it as a benefit. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.07,0:26:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s because he chose to be peaceable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.34,0:26:03.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you and I can do the same. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.35,0:26:05.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, we need to. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.35,0:26:07.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.35,0:26:11.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Because from time to time \Neach one of us will encounter a “Paul” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.39,0:26:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—someone who gives us correction \Nthat we need to hear, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.36,0:26:17.73,Default,,0,0,0,,but it comes to us in blunt terms, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.73,0:26:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps at a most inappropriate time, \Nand it stings. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.73,0:26:23.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And sometimes the counsel \Nthat stings the most \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.97,0:26:26.91,Default,,0,0,0,,is also the counsel we need the most. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.90,0:26:31.91,Default,,0,0,0,,If, like Peter, we choose to be peaceable, \Nwe’ll be able to take it \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.91,0:26:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,not only when someone wrongs us \Nbut also when someone “rights” us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.38,0:26:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,by giving us needed correction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.91,0:26:42.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s be honest, though, \Nit’s tough to do that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.78,0:26:46.58,Default,,0,0,0,,We can be so hypersensitive at times, \Nand no wonder. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.59,0:26:50.63,Default,,0,0,0,,We live in a world where it’s just common \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.63,0:26:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to blame someone else for our mistakes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.26,0:26:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,If someone breaks something, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.46,0:26:58.80,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s the manufacturer’s fault \Nfor not making it unbreakable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.80,0:27:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,A speeding ticket \N—that’s the policeman’s fault \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.00,0:27:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,because he had to meet a quota. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.00,0:27:05.70,Default,,0,0,0,,If a child fails English, \Nit’s the teacher’s fault \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.71,0:27:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,for not teaching English \Ngood enough, or well enough. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.88,0:27:14.49,Default,,0,0,0,,In this world, \Ncorrection is largely viewed as an insult, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.48,0:27:16.48,Default,,0,0,0,,not as a teaching tool. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.48,0:27:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,But God’s Word \Ndoes not support the world’s view. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.19,0:27:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible tells us of people \Nthat stayed in or went out of God’s favor \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.06,0:27:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,depending on how they responded to counsel. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.13,0:27:33.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So if we choose to remain bitter \Nat the person who corrected us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.07,0:27:35.07,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to remember this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.07,0:27:37.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We are letting our upset emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.14,0:27:40.78,Default,,0,0,0,,have far too much power over us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.78,0:27:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Resentment is heavy baggage \Nthat will only add to our load \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.68,0:27:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,on our journey to God’s new world, \Nand who needs that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.02,0:27:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, we need to be peaceable, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.39,0:27:55.39,Default,,0,0,0,,not only when we’re wronged \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.39,0:27:59.33,Default,,0,0,0,,but also when we’re righted \Nthrough correction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.33,0:28:01.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So to review: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.33,0:28:04.20,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we lighten our load \Nwhen someone upsets us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.20,0:28:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,First, like Gideon, \Nlook for the “grape harvest” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.97,0:28:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,—find something good about the person. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:10.47,0:28:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, like Peter, \Nbe willing to accept correction \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:14.74,0:28:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,regardless of the manner in which it’s given. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.05,0:28:24.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Those two suggestions \Ncan lighten our load when people upset us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.59,0:28:28.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s move \Non to our third and final point: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.32,0:28:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,when negative emotions overwhelm us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.63,0:28:35.63,Default,,0,0,0,,As imperfect humans, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.63,0:28:40.20,Default,,0,0,0,,we are prone to have \Na distorted view of ourselves. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:40.20,0:28:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,A few might ‘think more \Nof themselves than necessary,’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.11,0:28:47.11,Default,,0,0,0,,as Romans 12:3 says. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.11,0:28:49.68,Default,,0,0,0,,But others have the opposite problem \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.68,0:28:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,—thinking too little of themselves, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:52.85,0:28:56.62,Default,,0,0,0,,plagued with feelings of worthlessness. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.62,0:28:59.49,Default,,0,0,0,,When they look at themselves, \Nwhat they see \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.49,0:29:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,is a gross misrepresentation of reality, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.09,0:29:07.66,Default,,0,0,0,,as if viewing themselves \Nin a distorted fun house mirror. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.66,0:29:09.73,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, one Witness \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.73,0:29:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,quoted in the September 15, 2014, \NWatchtower said this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.74,0:29:18.41,Default,,0,0,0,,“When I think \Nabout everything I’ve done wrong, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.41,0:29:20.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“it can make me feel as if there’s no way \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.78,0:29:25.15,Default,,0,0,0,,anyone can ever love me, not even Jehovah.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.15,0:29:29.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Another, quoted \Nin the January 2006, Awake! said this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.38,0:29:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“I knew that Jehovah \Nhad forgiven me for my mistakes, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:33.15,0:29:35.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“but I did not want him to. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:35.39,0:29:39.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“I wanted to suffer \Nbecause I hated myself so much. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:39.69,0:29:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“While I knew that Jehovah \Ncould never have conceived \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.66,0:29:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“of a place . . . like Christendom’s hell, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.43,0:29:49.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I wanted him to invent one just for me.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:51.44,0:29:55.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as these examples illustrate, \Nour emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.14,0:30:00.88,Default,,0,0,0,,—which ironically Jehovah created \Nto enhance our love and our worship—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.88,0:30:05.89,Default,,0,0,0,,can sometimes turn against us \Nand make us feel condemned. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.89,0:30:09.63,Default,,0,0,0,,And that does more than just hinder our joy; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.62,0:30:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,it also hinders our ability \Nto give Jehovah full glory \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:13.33,0:30:16.23,Default,,0,0,0,,for the magnitude of his love. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.23,0:30:20.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So how can we cope with negative emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.44,0:30:22.51,Default,,0,0,0,,that at times overwhelm us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.50,0:30:27.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let’s look at Romans 7:22-25. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.41,0:30:31.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, here the apostle Paul \Ndescribes negative emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.08,0:30:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,that at times overwhelmed him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.08,0:30:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,And as we read these verses, \Ntry to detect two things: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.42,0:30:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,(1) what Paul could not control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.22,0:30:42.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and (2) what he could control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:42.29,0:30:45.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Romans 7, beginning with verse 22: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.99,0:30:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“I really delight in the law of God \Naccording to the man I am within, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.00,0:30:55.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“but I see in my body another law \Nwarring against the law of my mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.90,0:30:59.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“and leading me captive \Nto sin’s law that is in my body. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:59.87,0:31:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“Miserable man that I am! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:02.38,0:31:06.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“Who will rescue me \Nfrom the body undergoing this death? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.35,0:31:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks to God through Jesus Christ our Lord!”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.55,0:31:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s identify our two components. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.96,0:31:17.40,Default,,0,0,0,,First, what couldn’t Paul control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.39,0:31:20.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Occasional feelings of self-doubt \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.03,0:31:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,which Paul said made him feel miserable. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.13,0:31:25.13,Default,,0,0,0,,What could he control? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.13,0:31:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Once again, it’s his response. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.64,0:31:30.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And Paul’s response \Nis right there in verse 25: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.91,0:31:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“Thanks to God \Nthrough Jesus Christ our Lord!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.24,0:31:36.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Here Paul gives us the first key \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.41,0:31:38.91,Default,,0,0,0,,to coping with negative emotions: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.91,0:31:42.01,Default,,0,0,0,,meditate on the ransom. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.02,0:31:45.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Make it a personal study project \Nif necessary. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.65,0:31:49.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Collect scriptures from the Bible \Nand material from our publications \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.79,0:31:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,that build up appreciation \Nfor what Jesus’ death means \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.06,0:31:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,not just to the world of mankind in general \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:57.23,0:32:01.57,Default,,0,0,0,,but to each one of us as an individual. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.57,0:32:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Meditating on the ransom \Ncan help us cope with negative emotions, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:05.87,0:32:07.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:07.88,0:32:12.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Because as the April 1, 1995, \NWatchtower says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:12.41,0:32:17.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“Christ’s ransom sacrifice \Nis the most potent answer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.42,0:32:22.36,Default,,0,0,0,,to the satanic lie \Nthat we are worthless or unlovable.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.36,0:32:24.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s think about that statement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.63,0:32:28.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Why does it call the idea \Nthat we are worthless or unlovable \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.56,0:32:33.57,Default,,0,0,0,,not just a lie but a “satanic lie”? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.57,0:32:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, who really profits when we believe \Nthat we’re unlovable to Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.21,0:32:44.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Who really benefits when we wallow \Nin thoughts of self-condemnation? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.58,0:32:46.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Whose purpose is really served \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.91,0:32:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,when our emotions plague us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:48.92,0:32:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to the extent that we feel like giving up? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.32,0:32:55.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Obviously, it’s Satan. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.19,0:32:58.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And consider the irony of that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.19,0:33:02.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Who really has proved himself \Nunworthy of Jehovah’s love? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:02.36,0:33:03.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Him! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.87,0:33:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Who really is beyond Jehovah’s forgiveness? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.57,0:33:08.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Him! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.07,0:33:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Who really does the ransom not apply to? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.31,0:33:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Him! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.74,0:33:18.75,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet now, \Nin one of his greatest “crafty acts,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.75,0:33:21.09,Default,,0,0,0,,as Ephesians 6:11 calls it, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.08,0:33:25.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Satan tries to throw \Nall those feelings of condemnation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.25,0:33:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that he deserves on you and on me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.99,0:33:34.03,Default,,0,0,0,,The ransom gives us permission \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.03,0:33:37.33,Default,,0,0,0,,to throw off that heavy baggage. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.33,0:33:40.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Evidently, that’s what Paul did. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.10,0:33:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, at times \Nhe felt miserable about himself, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.94,0:33:47.81,Default,,0,0,0,,as we read at Romans 7:24. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.81,0:33:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,But he also wrote at Galatians 2:20: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.28,0:33:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“I live by faith in the Son of God, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.61,0:33:56.71,Default,,0,0,0,,who loved me \Nand handed himself over for me.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.72,0:33:59.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in stating that, \NPaul wasn’t being egotistical \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:59.89,0:34:03.06,Default,,0,0,0,,or thinking more of himself than necessary. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.06,0:34:06.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He simply understood \Na basic Scriptural truth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.73,0:34:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,—that Christ died for sinners, \Nnot for perfect people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.63,0:34:16.27,Default,,0,0,0,,The fact that Paul was so keenly aware \Nof his imperfections was evidence \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:16.27,0:34:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was the very kind of person \Nthat Jesus gave his life for. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.54,0:34:27.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The ransom helped Paul \Nrefute any feelings of self-doubt, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.55,0:34:29.95,Default,,0,0,0,,and it can do the same for us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.95,0:34:32.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, the April 1, 1995, Watchtower \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:32.95,0:34:35.62,Default,,0,0,0,,expresses that thought beautifully. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.62,0:34:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: “If life in this system \Nhas taught you to see yourself \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.59,0:34:41.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“as an obstacle too daunting \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.90,0:34:44.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“even for God’s immense love to surmount, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:44.97,0:34:47.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“. . . or your sins as too vast \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.44,0:34:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“even for the death \Nof his precious Son to cover, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.87,0:34:53.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“you have been taught a lie. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:53.74,0:34:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Reject such lies \Nwith all the repugnance that they deserve!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.35,0:35:01.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn’t that what we do \Nwith all of Satan’s other lies? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.08,0:35:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Do we accept the doctrine of the Trinity? No! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.72,0:35:07.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Do we believe in hellfire? No! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.09,0:35:10.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Do we believe that life evolved? No! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:10.56,0:35:14.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Do we believe that we are unlovable \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:14.53,0:35:17.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and worthless to Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:17.90,0:35:22.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Our answer to that question should be no, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:22.07,0:35:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and it should be just as decisive \Nas our no to the other questions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.87,0:35:27.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.07,0:35:29.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Because the idea that we are worthless \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.91,0:35:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,or unlovable to Jehovah is a false doctrine, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.72,0:35:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and we need to reject it just as firmly \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.82,0:35:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,as we would reject \Nany of Satan’s other God-dishonoring lies. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.23,0:35:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Meditating on the ransom can help us do that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:49.13,0:35:51.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But besides meditating on the ransom, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.47,0:35:54.61,Default,,0,0,0,,there’s something else we can do \Nto cope with negative emotions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.60,0:35:58.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at Psalm 61:2. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.61,0:36:01.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What David prayed for \Nin this verse presents us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:01.34,0:36:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,with another key to dealing \Nwith negative emotions, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.65,0:36:07.42,Default,,0,0,0,,including feelings of worthlessness. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.42,0:36:11.72,Default,,0,0,0,,At Psalm 61:2, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:11.72,0:36:13.72,Default,,0,0,0,,David says to Jehovah: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.72,0:36:16.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“From the ends of the earth \NI will cry out to you \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.59,0:36:19.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“when my heart is in despair. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.06,0:36:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Lead me onto a rock \Nthat is higher than I am.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:24.07,0:36:28.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Here, David is asking Jehovah \Nfor a different view, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.20,0:36:30.20,Default,,0,0,0,,an elevated one. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:30.20,0:36:32.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s what we need \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.21,0:36:34.58,Default,,0,0,0,,when negative emotions plague us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:34.58,0:36:38.25,Default,,0,0,0,,As David wrote, \Nwe need to be placed on a rock \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.25,0:36:40.25,Default,,0,0,0,,that is higher than ourselves, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:40.25,0:36:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,higher than our imperfect \Nand distorted reasoning. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.95,0:36:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Scriptural truths \Ncan help us do that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.49,0:36:50.49,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.49,0:36:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,when the heart is in despair, \Nas David wrote, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.36,0:36:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,we may feel that no one can love us, \Nnot even Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:59.07,0:37:02.54,Default,,0,0,0,,But the elevated view from the rock \Nreveals a Scriptural truth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.54,0:37:04.68,Default,,0,0,0,,—Romans 8:38, 39—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:04.67,0:37:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,nothing can “separate us from God’s love.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.51,0:37:11.45,Default,,0,0,0,,When the heart is in despair, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.45,0:37:16.26,Default,,0,0,0,,we feel that our mistakes \Nare too great for Jehovah to forgive. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:16.25,0:37:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,But the elevated view from the rock \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.32,0:37:21.16,Default,,0,0,0,,reveals a Scriptural truth—Romans 5:8: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.16,0:37:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“While we were yet sinners, \NChrist died for us.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.76,0:37:27.23,Default,,0,0,0,,As we mentioned before, \NJesus died for sinners, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.23,0:37:29.97,Default,,0,0,0,,not for perfect people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.96,0:37:32.36,Default,,0,0,0,,When the heart is in despair, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.37,0:37:35.27,Default,,0,0,0,,we can’t picture ourselves in Paradise \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.27,0:37:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,because in our heart we feel condemned. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:40.84,0:37:44.34,Default,,0,0,0,,But the elevated view from the rock \Nreveals a Scriptural truth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.35,0:37:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—1 John 3:20: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.35,0:37:50.92,Default,,0,0,0,,“God is greater than our hearts \Nand [he] knows all things,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.92,0:37:54.19,Default,,0,0,0,,including the reasons why we tend to think \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.19,0:37:56.63,Default,,0,0,0,,so negatively of ourselves. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.62,0:38:01.39,Default,,0,0,0,,The point is: Gradually we can replace \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.40,0:38:03.50,Default,,0,0,0,,lowly negative thoughts \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:03.50,0:38:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,with elevated Scriptural truths. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:06.47,0:38:08.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we just mentioned three of those truths. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.77,0:38:09.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one more. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.84,0:38:12.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at Malachi 3:17. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.77,0:38:14.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in its application, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.78,0:38:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Malachi 3 is talking \Nabout Jehovah’s spiritual temple. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:18.18,0:38:21.55,Default,,0,0,0,,But in principle, this verse \Nshows us the high value \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.55,0:38:24.99,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah places on his people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:24.99,0:38:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Malachi 3:17 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.96,0:38:31.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘And they will be mine,’ \Nsays Jehovah of armies, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.69,0:38:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,‘in the day \Nwhen I produce a special property’” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:35.50,0:38:40.11,Default,,0,0,0,,or, as the footnote renders it, \N“a treasured possession.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.10,0:38:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s stop there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.10,0:38:46.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice how proudly \NJehovah talks about his people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.44,0:38:49.34,Default,,0,0,0,,He says: “They will be mine.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.34,0:38:53.44,Default,,0,0,0,,He even calls his people \N“a special property.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.45,0:38:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And make no mistake, \Nthat term isn’t thrown into the Bible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:38:56.52,0:39:00.42,Default,,0,0,0,,just to make us feel good \Nor to give us empty praise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.42,0:39:03.96,Default,,0,0,0,,No, Jehovah’s people are special to him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:03.96,0:39:05.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.96,0:39:08.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Because he produced \Nthis property that we just read. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:08.70,0:39:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, \NJehovah is cultivating in each one of us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.87,0:39:15.01,Default,,0,0,0,,the very spiritual qualities \Nthat make us special to him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.10,0:39:22.11,Default,,0,0,0,,So again, going back to Psalm 61:2, \Nwhen the “heart is in despair,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.11,0:39:26.98,Default,,0,0,0,,as David wrote, we may only see \Nour failings and imperfections. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:26.98,0:39:30.35,Default,,0,0,0,,But the elevated view from the rock \Nreveals a Scriptural truth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.35,0:39:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—Malachi 3:17—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.35,0:39:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we are “a special property” to Jehovah \Ndespite our flaws. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.23,0:39:42.80,Default,,0,0,0,,And if it’s difficult for us to accept that, \Nthen we need to remember \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.80,0:39:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah is the one \Nwho sets the standard \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.33,0:39:49.10,Default,,0,0,0,,for what’s special here, not us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.10,0:39:54.11,Default,,0,0,0,,One sister who had \Nan extremely negative view of herself \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:54.11,0:39:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,was helped to reason on that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.28,0:39:58.85,Default,,0,0,0,,She says: \N“A spiritually mature sister helped me \N
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.85,0:40:02.46,Default,,0,0,0,,“to look at myself realistically \Nas an imperfect human \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.45,0:40:04.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“with strengths and weaknesses, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.52,0:40:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“no better or worse \Nthan any other brother or sister \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.19,0:40:09.49,Default,,0,0,0,,“struggling with imperfection. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:09.49,0:40:11.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“An elder greatly helped me too \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:11.66,0:40:14.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“by telling me \Nthat no one comes to Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:14.63,0:40:18.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“without being drawn by His spirit \N(that’s John 6:44). \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:18.37,0:40:21.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“So Jehovah must see \Nsomething lovable in me, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:21.90,0:40:26.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and who was I \Nto despise what Jehovah loves?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.27,0:40:29.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And notice how this sister \Nis slowly moving away \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:29.71,0:40:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,from that distorted mirror \Nand coming to see herself \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.35,0:40:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,the way Jehovah does. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.35,0:40:37.35,Default,,0,0,0,,We can do the same. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:37.35,0:40:39.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it easy? Absolutely not. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.85,0:40:41.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Second Corinthians 10:4 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.86,0:40:45.26,Default,,0,0,0,,talks about “strongly entrenched things” \Nthat we need to overturn, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:45.26,0:40:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and it lists “reasonings” \Nas one of those things. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:48.60,0:40:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that could include \Nour imperfect and distorted reasoning \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:52.83,0:40:55.17,Default,,0,0,0,,about our value to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:55.17,0:40:58.51,Default,,0,0,0,,That reasoning might be \Nso strongly entrenched \N
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.51,0:41:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,that we need \Nto keep praying about it, keep studying, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.08,0:41:06.22,Default,,0,0,0,,(or as we mentioned earlier) \Nkeep meditating on the ransom. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.21,0:41:10.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But as we gradually replace \Nlowly negative emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.15,0:41:12.72,Default,,0,0,0,,with elevated Scriptural truths, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.72,0:41:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ll be better able to move away \Nfrom that distorted mirror \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:16.72,0:41:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and see ourselves the way Jehovah does.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.63,0:41:23.63,Default,,0,0,0,,So to review: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:23.63,0:41:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we cope with negative emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:26.00,0:41:28.24,Default,,0,0,0,,that at times overwhelm us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:28.24,0:41:30.74,Default,,0,0,0,,First, meditate on the ransom. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.74,0:41:34.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It is the most potent answer \Nto the satanic lie \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:34.68,0:41:38.18,Default,,0,0,0,,that we are worthless \Nor unlovable to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:38.18,0:41:42.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, gradually replace \Nlowly negative thoughts \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.65,0:41:45.29,Default,,0,0,0,,with elevated Scriptural truths \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.29,0:41:49.33,Default,,0,0,0,,—truths that will help us \Nsee ourselves the way Jehovah does. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.32,0:41:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Those two suggestions \Ncan help us cope with negative emotions \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:53.49,0:41:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that have become a plague of our heart. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.33,0:42:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Now in conclusion, a final thought: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:01.77,0:42:04.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever plagues our heart, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.24,0:42:07.88,Default,,0,0,0,,even if it’s a situation \Nthat we haven’t touched on this evening, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:07.88,0:42:12.72,Default,,0,0,0,,remaining spiritually active \Nwill lighten our load. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.71,0:42:15.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we at Bethel are blessed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:15.08,0:42:17.18,Default,,0,0,0,,because we have plenty to do \Nin Jehovah’s work. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.18,0:42:19.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And really, wherever we serve, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.72,0:42:23.02,Default,,0,0,0,,theocratic activity \Nwill balance our thinking \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.02,0:42:27.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and help us to put \Nthe principles we discussed into practice. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.53,0:42:32.54,Default,,0,0,0,,But our strongest means of coping \Nwith any plague of our heart \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:32.53,0:42:35.70,Default,,0,0,0,,is identified at Psalm 62:1, 2. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.70,0:42:37.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read those verses. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.74,0:42:40.08,Default,,0,0,0,,What David says in Psalm 62 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.07,0:42:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,can lighten our load \Nand make it easier for us to carry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:44.25,0:42:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 62, beginning with verse 1: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:48.02,0:42:51.92,Default,,0,0,0,,“Indeed, I wait silently for God. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:51.92,0:42:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“My salvation comes from him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:54.66,0:42:57.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“Indeed, he is my rock and my salvation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:42:57.83,0:43:00.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“my secure refuge; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:00.36,0:43:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,I will never be greatly shaken.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:04.23,0:43:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s think about that last phrase \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:06.30,0:43:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“I will never be greatly shaken.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:09.20,0:43:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,What does that mean, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.21,0:43:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and how can it help us cope \Nwith the plague of our heart? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:15.54,0:43:18.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, to illustrate it, \Nlast year my wife and I were on a flight \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:18.38,0:43:22.99,Default,,0,0,0,,from El Paso to New York \Nwhen the plane hit turbulence. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:22.98,0:43:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And this wasn’t ordinary turbulence; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.79,0:43:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,this turbulence was so bad \Nthat the pilot told the flight attendants \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:29.12,0:43:31.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to sit down and fasten their seat belts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:31.46,0:43:34.96,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a nerve-racking experience. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:34.96,0:43:37.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Obviously, we survived. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.23,0:43:40.17,Default,,0,0,0,,But a day or two later, I did some research \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:40.17,0:43:42.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and I found out something about turbulence \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.77,0:43:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,that many passengers don’t know. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:45.34,0:43:47.34,Default,,0,0,0,,You know what it is? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:47.34,0:43:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s that planes are built \Nto handle turbulence, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:51.35,0:43:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,even the really bad kind. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:54.11,0:43:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, when the pilot says \Nhe’s searching for smoother air, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.12,0:44:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,he’s not doing it so much for our safety \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:02.12,0:44:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,as he is just for our comfort \Nand to keep the coffee in our cups. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:07.13,0:44:10.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Turbulence might shake a plane, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:10.30,0:44:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but the plane will not be greatly shaken. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:15.37,0:44:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,To cope with the plague of our heart, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:18.64,0:44:21.91,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to understand something similar \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.91,0:44:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,about the turbulence going on in our life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:25.88,0:44:30.15,Default,,0,0,0,,When we face a trial, \Nour tendency might be to panic, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:30.15,0:44:32.15,Default,,0,0,0,,to grip the armrests (so to speak), \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.15,0:44:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,to worry about what \Nthe next moment will bring, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:35.36,0:44:37.96,Default,,0,0,0,,to fear that we are going to crash. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:37.96,0:44:41.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But we can have confidence that, \Nas David said, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:41.30,0:44:43.30,Default,,0,0,0,,we will never be greatly shaken. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.30,0:44:46.44,Default,,0,0,0,,We can handle the turbulence \Nof any trial that comes our way. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:46.43,0:44:48.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And why? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.44,0:44:50.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Not because of our own strength, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:50.57,0:44:54.04,Default,,0,0,0,,but because we feel \Nas David expresses in verse 2: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:54.04,0:44:58.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“[Jehovah] is my rock and my salvation, \Nmy secure refuge.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:44:58.71,0:45:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,So yes, we may be shaken by our trial, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:02.35,0:45:07.36,Default,,0,0,0,,but with Jehovah’s help, \Nwe will never be greatly shaken. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:07.35,0:45:11.16,Default,,0,0,0,,By all means, then, \Nwhatever hardship we face \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.16,0:45:16.17,Default,,0,0,0,,—whether it’s circumstances \Nthat discourage us, people who upset us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:16.16,0:45:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,negative emotions that overwhelm us, \Nor anything else\N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:19.93,0:45:23.50,Default,,0,0,0,,—let us continue to make Jehovah \Nour secure refuge, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:45:23.50,0:45:26.15,Default,,0,0,0,,confident that he can help us cope \Nwith the plague of our heart. \N
